title: Sydney rental vacancy rate drops
text:
Rental vacancies in Sydney dropped to 2.9 per cent, the lowest in a year, led by areas such as Chatswood, Auburn and Arndell Park, the latest REINSW Residential Vacancy Rate Report shows.

September's decline from 3.6 per cent in August brought the city-wide level below 3 per cent for the first time since November, the Real Estate Institute of NSW report said.

Middle-ring suburbs enjoyed the biggest drop of 0.9 percentage points as the rate slipped to 3 per cent from 3.9 per cent.

Rents in the harbour city are falling, making it easier for tenants to take up accommodation. Separate data from Domain Group – majority-owned by Nine, publisher of The Australian Financial Review – last week showed large volumes of new stock on the market pulled house rents down an annual 4.5 per cent and unit rents down 4.6 per cent in the September quarter.

"We haven’t seen Sydney’s vacancy rates this low since October last year,” REINSW chief executive Tim McKibbin said.

"We do typically see vacancies decrease in the warmer months, so we can expect rates to remain low across NSW into the new year."
description: The September REINSW Residential Vacancy Rate Report says suburbs such as Neutral Bay, North Sydney and Forestville still have vacancy rates in excess of 5pc.
